title: Fish Tacos with Lime-Cilantro Crema
summary: The recipe Fish Tacos with Lime-Cilantro Crema could satisfy your Mexican craving in around 15 minutes. This gluten free and pescatarian recipe serves 4 and costs $3.22 per serving. This main course has 321 calories, 39g of protein, and 5g of fat per serving. Head to the store and pick up garlic clove, cream, ground cumin, and a few other things to make it today. To use up the lime rind you could follow this main course with the Key Lime Cupcakes as a dessert. 1 person were impressed by this recipe. All things considered, we decided this recipe deserves a spoonacular score of 90%. This score is super. Try Crispy Fish Tacos with Cilantro-Lime Crema, Grilled Fish Tacos with Mango Salsan and Cilantro Crema, and Fish Tacos with Lime Crema for similar recipes.

winePairing.pairingText: Fish works really well with Pinot Grigio, Gruener Veltliner, and Pinot Noir. Fish is as diverse as wine, so it's hard to pick wines that go with every fish. A crisp white wine, such as a pinot grigio or Grüner Veltliner, will suit any delicately flavored white fish. Meaty, strongly flavored fish such as salmon and tuna can even handle a light red wine, such as a pinot noir. The La Fiera Pinot Grigio with a 4 out of 5 star rating seems like a good match. It costs about 7 dollars per bottle.

productMatches.title: La Fiera Pinot Grigio
productMatches.description: This wine has a light straw color with green tints. It has a light floral and fruity bouquet featuring apples and pears. The palate is bright, fresh and dry showing nice balance and a lingering acidity perfect for a variety of lighter cuisine.Blend: 100% Pinot Grigio

instructions: Preheat oven to 425.                                                                                                To prepare crema, combine the first 8 ingredients in a small bowl; set aside.                                                                                                To prepare tacos, combine cumin and next 5 ingredients (through garlic powder) in a small bowl; sprinkle spice mixture evenly over both sides of fish. Place fish on a baking sheet coated with cooking spray. Bake at 425 for 9 minutes or until fish flakes easily when tested with a fork or until desired degree of doneness. Place fish in a bowl; break into pieces with a fork. Heat tortillas according to package directions. Divide fish evenly among tortillas; top each with 1/4 cup cabbage and 1 tablespoon crema.
